1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,580
In this lesson, we're going to now look at

2
00:00:02,580 --> 00:00:06,090
relationships between two qualitative variables,

3
00:00:06,090 --> 00:00:09,540
vehicle class and vehicle transmission.

4
00:00:09,540 --> 00:00:13,800
We're going to do this by using a clustered bar chart.

5
00:00:13,800 --> 00:00:17,985
To get started, let's load our Python libraries and

6
00:00:17,985 --> 00:00:22,955
Visualization libraries as normal and our fuel economy dataset.

7
00:00:22,955 --> 00:00:27,990
Now, the first thing we're going to do is a little bit of feature engineering.

8
00:00:27,990 --> 00:00:31,095
We need to extract the transmission type.

9
00:00:31,095 --> 00:00:35,710
Now, there are many different kinds of transmission types that our dataset looks at.

10
00:00:35,710 --> 00:00:42,975
But we're really only interested in the broad categories of automatic and manual.

11
00:00:42,975 --> 00:00:47,960
To do that, we're going to extract that by using

12
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:56,030
a Lambda function where we just look at the first word of each transmission type.

13
00:00:56,030 --> 00:01:02,195
For instance, you can see here that in the original DataFrame,

14
00:01:02,195 --> 00:01:05,930
the trans variable includes many types of

15
00:01:05,930 --> 00:01:11,540
automatics and we only want to take the first word in our Lambda function.

16
00:01:11,540 --> 00:01:13,145
We go all the way to the end.

17
00:01:13,145 --> 00:01:16,655
We now see we have a new feature called trans type,

18
00:01:16,655 --> 00:01:21,690
which includes automatic, but also manual cars.

19
00:01:22,040 --> 00:01:28,540
One way of depicting this relationship could be with a 2D Histogram Heatmap,

20
00:01:28,540 --> 00:01:30,140
like we saw before.

21
00:01:30,140 --> 00:01:35,270
However, there's actually a Seaborne function for this type of categorical heatmap.

22
00:01:35,270 --> 00:01:38,215
It's called the heatmap function.

23
00:01:38,215 --> 00:01:41,330
However, this function takes as an argument,

24
00:01:41,330 --> 00:01:45,920
a 2D array or DataFrame with the values to be depicted.

25
00:01:45,920 --> 00:01:49,000
The calling syntax is slightly different.

26
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:55,625
This means we have to do some summarization work ourselves before we can create our plot.

27
00:01:55,625 --> 00:01:57,815
To strike the summary process.

28
00:01:57,815 --> 00:02:01,955
First, I use group by to take our DataFrame

29
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:07,505
and group by vehicle class and transmission type.

30
00:02:07,505 --> 00:02:12,380
I want to know how many of each are in combined categories.

31
00:02:12,380 --> 00:02:14,900
I use the size method.

32
00:02:14,900 --> 00:02:16,575
We can see here,

33
00:02:16,575 --> 00:02:19,940
our DataFrame has now broken down by vehicle class and

34
00:02:19,940 --> 00:02:24,900
transmission type with a total number of count in each of these.

35
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:33,255
Now, this group by object is technically a series and we want to make it a DataFrame.

36
00:02:33,255 --> 00:02:43,040
To do that, we're going to use a reset index and then rename this last column to count.

37
00:02:43,040 --> 00:02:48,740
Finally, we're going to use this pivot function,

38
00:02:48,740 --> 00:02:52,945
this DataFrame pivot method to rearrange the data.

39
00:02:52,945 --> 00:02:56,330
We're going to pass it in the index that we're looking for,

40
00:02:56,330 --> 00:02:58,415
which is the V Class column.

41
00:02:58,415 --> 00:03:01,805
The column is going to be transmission type

42
00:03:01,805 --> 00:03:05,960
in the values for each cell is going to be count.

43
00:03:05,960 --> 00:03:11,900
Then we can put this directly in to our Seaborne heatmap object.

44
00:03:11,900 --> 00:03:15,250
This looks cool, but it's disappointing.

45
00:03:15,250 --> 00:03:20,630
It's really hard to compare the counts and transmission ratios from the colors alone.

46
00:03:20,630 --> 00:03:25,535
You can see that manual tends to be less popular than automatic,

47
00:03:25,535 --> 00:03:28,870
but beyond that, it's really hard to tell.

48
00:03:28,870 --> 00:03:34,730
One option we have is to add annotations with the cell counts in each cell.

49
00:03:34,730 --> 00:03:38,185
This will make the representation more tabular in nature.

50
00:03:38,185 --> 00:03:41,145
Let's do that. Here,

51
00:03:41,145 --> 00:03:44,465
we have a parameter called annot for annotation.

52
00:03:44,465 --> 00:03:46,390
We're going to put that to be true.

53
00:03:46,390 --> 00:03:51,320
The fm 't' is a formatter parameter and we're

54
00:03:51,320 --> 00:03:56,500
going to put d to ensure that all of the counts are listed as decimal values.

55
00:03:56,500 --> 00:03:58,545
This is much better.

56
00:03:58,545 --> 00:04:01,445
We still get the interpretation that we had before

57
00:04:01,445 --> 00:04:04,895
that there tend to be fewer manual cars than automatic.

58
00:04:04,895 --> 00:04:10,920
But now we can see quantitative variation much easier.

